                    </article>

                                                                                                </div>
                        

                        <p>If workers would become frustrated if they received lower tips than other workers, it could make tipping counterproductive, Glucksman postulated. He wrote that workers may feel obligated to work faster and move more customers through the line and thus earn more tips.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Multiple Brodhead Center employees declined to comment when asked about their opinions on tipping.</p>
<p>For now, a smile and greeting may mean just as much as a couple bucks. Scarlet, who makes salads at Farmstead, said that it makes her shifts a lot easier when customers are friendly and interactive.</p>
<p>“I’ll have a bad day, and then they ask me, ‘How was your day?’” she said, “and it just makes me feel good.”</p>
